SIMPLE: wormwood
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Wormwood
<hw>Worm"wood</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS.
<ets>werm<?/d</ets>, akin to OHG. <ets>wermuota</ets>,
<ets>wormuota</ets>, G. <ets>wermuth</ets>, <ets>wermut</ets>; of
uncertain origin.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A composite plant (<spn>Artemisia
Absinthium</spn>), having a bitter and slightly aromatic taste, formerly
used as a tonic and a vermifuge, and to protect woolen garments from
moths. It gives the peculiar flavor to the cordial called absinthe. The
volatile oil is a narcotic poison. The term is often extended to other
species of the same genus.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Anything very bitter or grievous;
bitterness.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Lest there should be among you a root that beareth gall and
<qex>wormwood</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Deut. xxix. 18.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Roman wormwood</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>an
American weed (<spn>Ambrosia artemisiaefolia</spn>); hogweed.</cd> --
<col><b>Tree wormwood</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>a species of
Artemisia (probably <spn>Artemisia variabilis</spn>) with woody
stems.</cd> -- <col><b>Wormwood hare</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>a
variety of the common hare (<spn>Lepus timidus</spn>); -- so named from
its color.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Wormy</ent>⟦br⟧
